<h1>Qatar Visa Guide 2026</h1>
<p>Qatar's visa system has undergone significant reform, particularly following the labor law changes introduced ahead of and after the 2022 FIFA World Cup. The dismantling of the kafala system, introduction of job mobility, and abolition of exit permits have modernized the framework substantially. This guide covers the main visa categories available to expatriates in Qatar, along with requirements, costs, and practical advice for 2026.</p>

<p>The reforms represent a fundamental shift in how Qatar manages its expatriate workforce. Before 2020, workers needed employer permission to change jobs or leave the country. Today, Qatar's labor mobility framework is among the most progressive in the Gulf region. Workers can change employers after serving contractual notice, and exit permits are no longer required. The Workers' Support and Insurance Fund provides financial protection for employees whose employers fail to meet obligations. These changes have improved Qatar's international standing and made it a more attractive destination for skilled professionals from around the world.</p>

{qatarVisas.types.map((visa) => (<><h2>{visa.name}</h2><p><strong>Duration:</strong> {visa.duration}</p><p>{visa.process}</p><p><strong>Estimated cost:</strong> {visa.cost}</p><h3>Requirements</h3><ul>{visa.requirements.map((r) => <li>{r}</li>)}</ul></>))}

